Hi @DentonGentry,

Thanks for guiding me. I tried following the above steps:
I added an authkey along with a tag.
sudo tailscale up --auth-key=tskey-auth-k4******CNTRL-FD5yb************CDVwXmp9DXY33fg --advertise-tags=tag:server

// Example/default ACLs for unrestricted connections.
{
	// Declare static groups of users. Use autogroups for all users or users with a specific role.
	"groups": {
		"group:sre": ["vaghulkumar@gmail.com", "khoa.hng@qbots.ai"],
	},

	// Define the tags which can be applied to devices and by which users.
	"tagOwners": {
		"tag:server": ["vaghulkumar@gmail.com", "khoa.hng@qbots.ai"],
	},

	// Define access control lists for users, groups, autogroups, tags,
	// Tailscale IP addresses, and subnet ranges.
	"acls": [
		// Allow all connections.
		// Comment this section out if you want to define specific restrictions.
		{"action": "accept", "src": ["*"], "dst": ["*:*"]},
	],

	// Define users and devices that can use Tailscale SSH.
	"ssh": [
		// Allow all users to SSH into their own devices in check mode.
		{
			"action": "accept",
			"src":    ["group:sre"],
			"dst":    ["autogroup:self"],
			"users":  ["autogroup:nonroot", "root"],
		},
	],
}

I wanted to enable the ssh so used the below command:
sudo tailscale up --auth-key=tskey-auth-k4******CNTRL-FD5yb************CDVwXmp9DXY33fg  --advertise-tags=tag:server --ssh

Getting the below error :
Tailscale SSH enabled, but access controls don't allow anyone to access this device. Ask your admin to update your tailnet's ACLs to allow access.

Just wanted to make sure 2 users specified are able to use the devices via ssh, and if the auth key expires the device should still remain active and for next batch even if we generate a new key, it works like the first ones.

And regarding the disable expiry key, as per my understanding from your message, we would be using all the devices thorought, so I believe the best option would be to disable expiry key, unless you disagree.
